    corrupt data used by a cloned SKB that has already been handed off into the network stack. - A packet SKB
    can be constructed whose tail is far beyond its end, causing out-of-bounds heap data to be considered part
    of the SKB's data. I have tested that this can be used by a malicious USB device to send a bogus ICMPv6
    Echo Request and receive an ICMPv6 Echo Reply in response that contains random kernel heap data. It's
    probably also possible to get OOB writes from this on a little-endian system somehow - maybe by triggering
    skb_cow() via IP options processing -, but I haven't tested that. (CVE-2022-48805)

Note that Nessus relies on the presence of the package as reported by the vendor.");
